<subSubSection id="87FB6554366BAB12FEDEF803F4FAF264" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="CF5E36DF366BAB12FEDEF803F4FAF264" blockId="1.[264,1324,1391,1897]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis id="FD95EACD366BAB12FEDEF803F120F1C5" box="[264,383,1391,1416]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Distinguished from the two other known South American freshwater sciaenid genera (
<taxonomicName id="08E14D5C366BAB12FEBCF8FBF1B8F1FD" authorityName="Agassiz in Spix &amp; Agassiz" authorityYear="1831" box="[362,487,1431,1456]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" genus="Pachyurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FD95EACD366BAB12FEBCF8FBF1B8F1FD" box="[362,487,1431,1456]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Pachyurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="08E14D5C366BAB12FDF0F8FBF2EDF1FD" authorityName="T.N.Gill" authorityYear="1861" box="[550,690,1431,1456]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Plagioscion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FD95EACD366BAB12FDF0F8FBF2EDF1FD" box="[550,690,1431,1456]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Plagioscion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) by the following combination of characters: mouth inferior, presence of three mental barbels, the swimbladder with a pair log posterior branches projecting from shorter paired anterior appendages (
<figureCitation id="57DA2A5A366BAB12FC32F88BF476F24C" box="[996,1065,1511,1537]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[264,367,870,894]" captionTargetBox="[441,1074,317,854]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Ventral view of the swimbladder of Pachypops fourcroi (A) and P. pigmaeus n. sp. (B). Not to scale." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/168634/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Fig. 
<number id="792924F8366BAB12FBCAF88BF476F24C" box="[1052,1065,1511,1537]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
), and presence of the expanded haemal spine on the first caudal vertebra (
<figureCitation id="57DA2A5A366BAB12FCBDFB63F3EBF264" box="[875,948,1551,1577]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[264,367,1787,1811]" captionTargetBox="[306,1286,974,1761]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[297,1290,966,1770]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Lateral view of the anal fin and associated vertebra of Pachypops trifilis. Scale bar is 5 mm; cvert, first caudal vertebrae; hsc 1, haemal spine of the first caudal vertebrae; ppt 1, first pterigyophore of anal fin." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155564/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Fig. 
<number id="792924F8366BAB12FC74FB63F3EBF264" box="[930,948,1551,1577]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
). Gender masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="87FB6554366BAB10FEEEFB5BF43FF773" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="CF5E36DF366BAB12FEEEFB5BF2A9F324" blockId="1.[264,1324,1391,1897]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis id="FD95EACD366BAB12FEEEFB5BF1EBF21D" box="[312,436,1591,1616]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Comments</emphasis>
. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="AB704B2E366BAB12FDBFFB5BF350F21C" author="Sasaki" box="[617,783,1591,1617]" firstAuthor="Sasaki" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" pagination="1 - 137" refId="ref10071" refString="Sasaki, K. (1989) Phylogeny of the family Sciaenidae, with notes on its zoogeography (Teleostei, Perciformes). Memories of the Faculty of Fisheries Hokkaido University, 36, 1 - 137." type="journal article" year="1989">
Sasaki (
<number id="792924F8366BAB12FD11FB5BF359F21C" box="[711,774,1591,1617]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="1989.0">1989</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="08E14D5C366BAB12FCCAFB5BF3C2F21D" authorityName="Gill" authorityYear="1861" box="[796,925,1591,1616]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Pachypops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FD95EACD366BAB12FCCAFB5BF3C2F21D" box="[796,925,1591,1616]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Pachypops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized phylogenetically by its swimbladder with a pair of anterior appendages (see 
<figureCitation id="57DA2A5A366BAB12FC01FB33F443F234" box="[983,1052,1631,1657]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[264,367,870,894]" captionTargetBox="[441,1074,317,854]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Ventral view of the swimbladder of Pachypops fourcroi (A) and P. pigmaeus n. sp. (B). Not to scale." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/168634/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Fig. 
<number id="792924F8366BAB12FBD9FB33F443F234" box="[1039,1052,1631,1657]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
), the possession of an unpored median barbel, and the possession of a pair of mental barbels. An unpublished phylogenetic study of South American freshwater sciaenids done by the author of the present paper reveals that the species of 
<taxonomicName id="08E14D5C366BAB12FD3CFBBBF334F2BD" authorityName="Gill" authorityYear="1861" box="[746,875,1751,1776]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Pachypops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FD95EACD366BAB12FD3CFBBBF334F2BD" box="[746,875,1751,1776]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Pachypops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share not only those synapomorphies listed by 
<bibRefCitation id="AB704B2E366BAB12FEA2FB93F24AF354" author="Sasaki" box="[372,533,1791,1817]" firstAuthor="Sasaki" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" pagination="1 - 137" refId="ref10071" refString="Sasaki, K. (1989) Phylogeny of the family Sciaenidae, with notes on its zoogeography (Teleostei, Perciformes). Memories of the Faculty of Fisheries Hokkaido University, 36, 1 - 137." type="journal article" year="1989">
Sasaki (
<number id="792924F8366BAB12FE06FB93F252F354" box="[464,525,1791,1817]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="1989.0">1989</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
but also an expanded haemal spine on the first caudal vertebra (see 
<figureCitation id="57DA2A5A366BAB12FEDEFA4BF10FF30C" box="[264,336,1831,1857]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[264,367,1787,1811]" captionTargetBox="[306,1286,974,1761]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[297,1290,966,1770]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Lateral view of the anal fin and associated vertebra of Pachypops trifilis. Scale bar is 5 mm; cvert, first caudal vertebrae; hsc 1, haemal spine of the first caudal vertebrae; ppt 1, first pterigyophore of anal fin." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155564/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Fig. 
<number id="792924F8366BAB12FEE9FA4BF10FF30C" box="[319,336,1831,1857]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
). These four synapomorphies are assumed to be homoplastic with other perciforms in the final most parsimonious phylogeny.
</paragraph>
